english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Delight in Heaven
  author: Byeon Gyeyeol
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Pavilion of Delight in Heaven is where our former king delights to wander and rest. In the nineteenth year of his reign, in the eighth month of autumn, he relinquished the throne to our present sovereign and, taking advantage of the harvest's respite, journeyed eastward to view the land. There stood a hill, lofty and rounded like an overturned cauldron, called Mount Terrace. Ascending it and gazing in all directions, one beholds the great river winding through ponds, the waters flowing and rippling without end, while ridge upon ridge of peaks emerges in sequence, encircling the hill like courtiers paying homage, like stars circling the pole star. Truly, here is a paradise wrought by heaven itself.

    The former king commanded that a retreat be built upon the northeastern corner of this hill to shelter from wind and rain, and upon the summit a pavilion was erected. He ordered his chief minister Park Eon to name the pavilion. Park Eon, drawing upon the Book of Changes, offered the two characters for "delight in heaven," thereby encompassing the essence of the former king's virtuous conduct and inscribing within the pavilion's name a mark of today's joy. I was commanded to compose this record.

    I reflect thus: Heaven is but principle itself, and delight is that which accords naturally with principle without forcing. The true essence of the limitless and the refined vital force of yin, yang, and the five phases merged mysteriously in conception, and thus was man born. The heavenly principle bestowed upon mankind is uniform in all. Yet among common people, their vital nature is mixed and clouded by material desire. Though they strive to follow heavenly principle, they cannot succeed. How much less can they achieve that natural accord which asks no effort?

    Contemplating our former king: heaven-endowed in gift, pre-eminent among all creatures, his luminous clarity abides within, and virtue is his constant practice. Thus all his actions are nothing but the flowing forth of heavenly principle. In his youth, grieving the passing of his sainted mother, he withdrew from worldly affairs and kept vigil at her tomb. When the former dynasty's end drew near with a foolish ruler and cruel ministers plotting against our great founder, he raised the banner of righteousness, established our nation, and elevated the founder to the throne of ten thousand chariots. In the year of the Tiger, when treacherous ministers, seizing upon our founder's illness, conspired with a young prince to sow chaos, he perceived their scheme and destroyed it, bringing peace to the state. The people called for his succession, yet he yielded to the senior line, honoring the principle of primogeniture. Since his ascension, he has constantly grieved that he could not attend upon our founder morning and evening. In the year of the Dog, desiring to relinquish the throne to fulfill his filial longing, he was prevented by the steadfast remonstrations of his ministers and by the founder himself. Three years later, when the founder departed to heaven, the former king's sorrow knew no bounds. He observed the full rites of mourning and, when presenting the founder at the ancestral temple, though rains had been falling, heaven cleared the very evening of the ceremony, only to resume three days hence—heaven itself bearing witness to his filial devotion.

    He has lavished love and reverence upon the present king with ever-deepening sincerity, a constancy unknown to all histories. By releasing Hoean without legal punishment, he followed the example of the great Shun in preserving his elder brother's wholeness, declining to emulate the Duke of Zhou's severity. By preserving the Wang lineage and securing their livelihood, he demonstrated the vast generosity of heaven and earth regarding the realm as public trust—following the principle by which Tang and Wu preserved the kingdoms of Qi and Song even as they transformed the age.

    In his relations with the great nation, receiving twice the imperial mandate, the son of heaven himself has praised his utmost sincerity. In his treatment of smaller states with benevolence, pirates who plagued the seas for fifty years have now surrendered, bowing their foreheads in submission, desiring to become his subjects. In the palace, harmony radiates; in conducting sacrifices, reverence is solemn. He has elevated the loyal and righteous while removing the treacherous. He hearkens to remonstrance, loves learning, honors frugality, and practices economy. He is mindful of heaven's warnings and compassionate toward the people's suffering. All that he has cultivated within his heart and manifest in his conduct flows purely from principle—no forced striving, but the very nature of our former king expressing itself.

    During twenty years, all regions have known peace. The granaries overflow with plenty. No warfare has touched the people. Heaven has sent sweet dew, and an age of supreme tranquility prevails—rarer than any recorded in antiquity. Can we doubt the words of the ancient sages: "Follow heavenly principle and nothing shall be amiss"?

    When last year he relinquished the throne, he was not weary with age, nor had illness incapacitated him, nor was he compelled by circumstances beyond his control. Though great and small officials wept together in the courtyard for days, unable to turn the will of heaven, he cast off the throne as one sheds a garment—an act unprecedented among all the rulers of antiquity. Now our present sovereign, possessed of keen wisdom and filial piety, gentle and diligent, receives each command with reverence and bears the heavy trust of the realm, thereby alleviating the former king's anxieties. This too was the occasion for building this pavilion.

    Observing this pavilion: when spring winds blow gently, fair flowers burst forth, their red and green spreading in splendor. Summer sun beats down like a furnace upon the earth, yet cool breezes fill the sitting place. When autumn tints the mountains and rivers, the water becomes a mirror and the hills a brocade screen, reflecting all around. When early snows first drift, gazing from the balcony, a thousand li appear as one color. When the former king receives the present sovereign, wine is shared, and without words they entrust their hearts to one another. The sovereign moves among them with fraternal affection and filial reverence, with paternal tenderness and dutiful love. Can joy in all the world exceed this?

    What the former king delights in is heavenly principle; what he does not delight in is heavenly rank. This is the same principle by which the sage-kings Shun and Yu possessed all under heaven yet claimed nothing for themselves. Yet how could the great concerns of the state and the people ever slip from his mind, even for a moment?

    When the kite soars through heaven and the fish leaps in the pond, we see the vastness of the Way. The mountain of Great Accumulation and the waters of Repeated Obstacles are what the benevolent and the wise love to contemplate. Heaven moves above without ceasing—the primal breath shines forth. Earth rests below in stillness—the generous virtue is revealed. Our former king, ascending this pavilion and looking up at heaven and down at earth, achieves a subtle harmony with the principle of heaven and earth and enjoys a joy that flows naturally. How can mere words or brush capture even a ten-thousandth part of this?

    What I have written records the truth of the former king's delight in heavenly principle as manifested in all his conduct. Since this truth is known to all, may we perceive the genuine nature of heaven's gift, be moved and inspired, and each honor our parents as parents and our elders as elders, fulfilling the way of human relationships and sharing in the former king's joy. The refinement of our Joseon's culture rivals that of ancient Yao and Zhou, and the permanence of the royal enterprise shall endure as long as hills and mountains, rivers and streams—endless and eternal. O, how glorious it is!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Book of Changes (I Ching) hexagrams 'Great Accumulation' and 'Repeated Obstacles' referenced here symbolize accumulation of virtue and navigating through difficulty—principles valued by the benevolent and wise.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Shun and Yu alludes to the Confucian ideal of sage-rulers who possessed the throne yet remained detached from its honors, prioritizing their duty to the people.
  - key: ''
    value: Park Eon, the chief minister who named the pavilion, drew the name from the Commentary on the Appended Phrases of the I Ching, connecting the pavilion to classical wisdom and virtue.
